				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\mathrm{min}}_{l}E{\left[R-l\left(T\right)\right]}^{2}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M58"><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">min</mml:mi><mml:mi>l</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mi>E</mml:mi><mml:msup><mml:mrow><mml:mfenced close="]" open="["><mml:mi>R</mml:mi><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mi>l</mml:mi><mml:mfenced close=")" open="("><mml:mi>T</mml:mi></mml:mfenced></mml:mfenced></mml:mrow><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:msup></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4288_Article_IEq28.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>, <italic>which equals</italic><inline-formula id="IEq29"><alternatives><tex-math id="M59">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$E\left[R|T\right]$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M60"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>E</mml:mi><mml:mfenced close="]" open="["><mml:mi>R</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">|</mml:mo><mml:mi>T</mml:mi></mml:mfenced></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4288_Article_IEq29.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>.</p>
        <p>This proposition motivates us to estimate g by minimizing the sum of squares<disp-formula id="Equa"><alternatives><tex-math id="M61">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\sum_{i=1}^{n}{\left[{r}_{i}-g\left({t}_{i}\right)\right]}^{2}.$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M62" display="block"><mml:mrow><mml:munderover><mml:mo>∑</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mi>i</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mi>n</mml:mi></mml:munderover><mml:msup><mml:mrow><mml:mfenced close="]" open="["><mml:msub><mml:mi>r</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mi>g</mml:mi><mml:mfenced close=")" open="("><mml:msub><mml:mi>t</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:mfenced></mml:mfenced></mml:mrow><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:msup><mml:mo>.</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4288_Article_Equa.gif" position="anchor"/></alternatives></disp-formula></p>
        <p>Finally, we consider the more practical situations. Suppose a portion <inline-formula id="IEq30"><alternatives><tex-math id="M63">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$1-\lambda (&lt;0.5)$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M64"><mml:mrow><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mi>λ</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mo>&lt;</mml:mo><mml:mn>0.5</mml:mn><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4288_Article_IEq30.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> of transcripts are differentially expressed (DE) by a sufficiently large amount. Then the undifferentiated transcripts can serve as the invariant set of genes for the pairwise normalization, and denote their indices by <inline-formula id="IEq31"><alternatives><tex-math id="M65">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$U$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M66"><mml:mi>U</mml:mi></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4288_Article_IEq31.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>. Now Assumption R2 is replaced by</p>
      </sec>
      <sec id="FPar3">
        <title>
          <bold>Assumption R3</bold>
        </title>
        <p id="Par51"><inline-formula id="IEq901"><alternatives><tex-math id="M67">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$E\left( {R_{i} {|}g\left( {T_{i} } \right)} \right) = g\left( {T_{i} } \right),\;{\text{for}}\;i \in U.$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M68"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>E</mml:mi><mml:mfenced close=")" open="("><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mi>R</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false">|</mml:mo><mml:mi>g</mml:mi><mml:mfenced close=")" open="("><mml:msub><mml:mi>T</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:mfenced></mml:mrow></mml:mfenced><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mi>g</mml:mi><mml:mfenced close=")" open="("><mml:msub><mml:mi>T</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:mfenced><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mspace width="0.277778em"/><mml:mtext>for</mml:mtext><mml:mspace width="0.277778em"/><mml:mi>i</mml:mi><mml:mo>∈</mml:mo><mml:mi>U</mml:mi><mml:mo>.</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4288_Article_IEq901.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>Then we estimate <italic>g</italic> by minimizing<disp-formula id="Equb"><alternatives><tex-math id="M69">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\sum_{i\in U}{\left[{r}_{i}-g\left({t}_{i}\right)\right]}^{2}.$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M70" display="block"><mml:mrow><mml:munder><mml:mo>∑</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mi>i</mml:mi><mml:mo>∈</mml:mo><mml:mi>U</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:munder><mml:msup><mml:mrow><mml:mfenced close="]" open="["><mml:msub><mml:mi>r</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mi>g</mml:mi><mml:mfenced close=")" open="("><mml:msub><mml:mi>t</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:mfenced></mml:mfenced></mml:mrow><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:msup><mml:mo>.</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4288_Article_Equb.gif" position="anchor"/></alternatives></disp-formula></p>
        <p id="Par52">Since <inline-formula id="IEq32"><alternatives><tex-math id="M71">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$U$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M72"><mml:mi>U</mml:mi></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4288_Article_IEq32.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> is unknown, we use least trimmed squares (LTS) to minimize the trimmed sum of squares, in the meantime, capture the set of undifferentiated transcripts. Because LTS removes the transcripts with large residuals, which usually are DE transcripts, the correspondence justifies the estimates of LTS.</p>
      </sec>
    </sec>
    <sec id="Sec4">
      <title>Parametrization</title>
      <p id="Par53">We parameterize <inline-formula id="IEq33"><alternatives><tex-math id="M73">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$g\left(t\right)$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M74"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>g</mml:mi><mml:mfenced close=")" open="("><mml:mi>t</mml:mi></mml:mfenced></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4288_Article_IEq33.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> by a simple linear function <inline-formula id="IEq34"><alternatives><tex-math id="M75">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\alpha +\beta t$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M76"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>α</mml:mi><mml:mo>+</mml:mo><mml:mi>β</mml:mi><mml:mi>t</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4288_Article_IEq34.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>. Consider the regression model<disp-formula id="Equ2"><label>2</label><alternatives><tex-math id="M77">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${r}_{i}=\alpha +\beta {t}_{i}+{\varepsilon }_{i},$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M78" display="block"><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mi>r</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mi>α</mml:mi><mml:mo>+</mml:mo><mml:mi>β</mml:mi><mml:msub><mml:mi>t</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>+</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>ε</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>,</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4288_Article_Equ2.gif" position="anchor"/></alternatives></disp-formula>where <inline-formula id="IEq35"><alternatives><tex-math id="M79">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${r}_{i}={\mathrm{log}}_{2}\left({R}_{i}+1\right)$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M80"><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mi>r</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">log</mml:mi><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mfenced close=")" open="("><mml:msub><mml:mi>R</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>+</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mfenced></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4288_Article_IEq35.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> and <inline-formula id="IEq36"><alternatives><tex-math id="M81">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${t}_{i}={\mathrm{log}}_{2}\left({T}_{i}+1\right)$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M82"><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mi>t</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">log</mml:mi><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mfenced close=")" open="("><mml:msub><mml:mi>T</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>+</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mfenced></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4288_Article_IEq36.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> are the log counts. The logarithmic transformation plays the role of variance stabilization to meet the assumption of homoscedasticity in the regression models.</p>
      <p id="Par54">The normalized abundance/count of <inline-formula id="IEq37"><alternatives><tex-math id="M83">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${T}_{i}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M84"><mml:msub><mml:mi>T</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4288_Article_IEq37.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> with respect to the given reference is then  <inline-formula id="IEq38"><alternatives><tex-math id="M85">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\widehat{t}}_{i}=\widehat{g}\left({t}_{i}\right)=\widehat{\alpha }+\widehat{\beta }{t}_{i}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M86"><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>t</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">^</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>g</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">^</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mfenced close=")" open="("><mml:msub><mml:mi>t</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:mfenced><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>α</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">^</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mo>+</mml:mo><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>β</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">^</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:msub><mml:mi>t</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4288_Article_IEq38.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> in the scale of log counts, or <inline-formula id="IEq39"><alternatives><tex-math id="M87">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\widehat{T}}_{i}={2}^{\widehat{g}\left({t}_{i}\right)}-1={2}^{\widehat{\alpha }}{\left({T}_{i}+1\right)}^{\widehat{\beta }}-1$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M88"><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>T</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">^</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:msup><mml:mrow><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>g</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">^</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mfenced close=")" open="("><mml:msub><mml:mi>t</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:mfenced></mml:mrow></mml:msup><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:msup><mml:mrow><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>α</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">^</mml:mo></mml:mover></mml:msup><mml:msup><mml:mrow><mml:mfenced close=")" open="("><mml:msub><mml:mi>T</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>+</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mfenced></mml:mrow><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>β</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">^</mml:mo></mml:mover></mml:msup><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4288_Article_IEq39.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> in the scale of raw counts. If <inline-formula id="IEq40"><alternatives><tex-math id="M89">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\beta =1$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M90"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>β</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4288_Article_IEq40.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> (single parameter form), <inline-formula id="IEq41"><alternatives><tex-math id="M91">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\widehat{T}}_{i}={2}^{\widehat{\alpha }}{T}_{i}+\left({2}^{\widehat{\alpha }}-1\right)\approx {2}^{\widehat{\alpha }}{T}_{i}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M92"><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>T</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">^</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:msup><mml:mrow><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>α</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">^</mml:mo></mml:mover></mml:msup><mml:msub><mml:mi>T</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>+</mml:mo><mml:mfenced close=")" open="("><mml:msup><mml:mrow><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>α</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">^</mml:mo></mml:mover></mml:msup><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mfenced><mml:mo>≈</mml:mo><mml:msup><mml:mrow><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>α</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">^</mml:mo></mml:mover></mml:msup><mml:msub><mml:mi>T</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4288_Article_IEq41.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>, the normalization is almost a scaling. If <inline-formula id="IEq42"><alternatives><tex-math id="M93">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\beta$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M94"><mml:mi>β</mml:mi></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4288_Article_IEq42.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> is a free parameter (double parameter form), <inline-formula id="IEq43"><alternatives><tex-math id="M95">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\widehat{T}}_{i}={2}^{\widehat{\alpha }}{\left({T}_{i}+1\right)}^{\widehat{\beta }}-1$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M96"><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>T</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">^</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:msup><mml:mrow><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>α</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">^</mml:mo></mml:mover></mml:msup><mml:msup><mml:mrow><mml:mfenced close=")" open="("><mml:msub><mml:mi>T</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>+</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mfenced></mml:mrow><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>β</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">^</mml:mo></mml:mover></mml:msup><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4288_Article_IEq43.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>, the resulting power law represents a simple nonlinear transform from <inline-formula id="IEq44"><alternatives><tex-math id="M97">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${T}_{i}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M98"><mml:msub><mml:mi>T</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4288_Article_IEq44.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> to <inline-formula id="IEq45"><alternatives><tex-math id="M99">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\tilde{T }}_{i}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M100"><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>T</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">~</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4288_Article_IEq45.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> and vice versa. It means the scaling coefficients of the read counts of transcripts at different expression levels are allowed to be different. Thus, it has higher flexibility to model the possible non-uniformness in the steps of isolation, amplification, and sequencing of transcripts at low and high expression levels.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="Sec5">
      <title>Least trimmed squares regression</title>
      <p id="Par55">Now we consider the parameter estimation of the regression model (<xref rid="Equ2" ref-type="">2</xref>). Given a constant integer <inline-formula id="IEq46"><alternatives><tex-math id="M101">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
